<paragraph blockId="117.[189,1399,1240,1481]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
<taxonomicName authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,594,1240,1266]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lobulata" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[189,594,1240,1266]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) lobulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[604,698,1240,1266]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[862,1028,1240,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="radula" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[862,1028,1240,1267]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">S. (A.) radula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[1046,1258,1240,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="raduloides" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[1046,1258,1240,1267]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">S. (A.) raduloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subradula" subGenus="Asiosphegina">S. (A.) subradula</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Except for the characters mentioned in the key, it is distinguished by having the dorsal lobe of male surstylus on both sides equally wide (wider on the left side in the other species) and by having the ventral lobe of the right side surstylus with notched posterior margin (even margin in the others). All the species mentioned resemble 
<taxonomicName authority="Huo, Ren &amp; Zheng, 2007" authorityName="Huo, Ren &amp; Zheng" authorityYear="2007" box="[573,1329,1384,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrapicula" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[573,1014,1384,1410]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) nigrapicula</emphasis>
Huo, Ren &amp; Zheng, 2007
</taxonomicName>
, from 
<collectingCountry box="[189,263,1420,1446]" name="China" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">China</collectingCountry>
. The latter differs by having all the setae posteriorly on male tergum IV rather thin and those on the right side all short, shorter than on the left side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="117" pageNumber="118" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="117.[189,324,1521,1547]" box="[189,324,1521,1547]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1521,1547]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1521,1547]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="117.[189,1398,1569,1630]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[650,748,1569,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lobulata">
<emphasis box="[650,748,1569,1595]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">lobulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘having lobes’ and referring to the lobes on the male superior lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
